WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:04.760
Concentric circles, of course, but I'll explain it one way. And

00:00:04.760 --> 00:00:07.840
there's probably other ways to think about this as well. In my

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:11.600
eyes, the business analyst is there every day, trying to

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:15.480
respond to the questions at hand for the day or the week, or

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:19.280
maybe the two weeks, most of the stuff that they are working on

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:23.480
is going to be relatively one off, right? Hey, can you help me

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:25.639
figure out this carrier problem this week? Can you help me

00:00:25.639 --> 00:00:30.160
figure out why a vendor isn't shipping on time this week? And

00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:34.880
then those insights or those discoveries, ultimately, we want

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:38.040
to be able to do that in a repeat fashion. So I kind of see

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:42.000
that's where the technical problem solvers can bring their

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:45.480
more technical skills in and say, Oh, that's great that we

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:49.279
found that let's do that over and over again. So right,

00:00:49.279 --> 00:00:52.599
business analysts, more ad hoc one offs, and then the technical

00:00:52.599 --> 00:00:54.759
problem solvers, we're trying to scale it up and make it

00:00:54.759 --> 00:00:59.599
repeatable. With that said, the technical problem solvers also

00:00:59.599 --> 00:01:04.080
sometimes are working on ad hoc, but maybe we need to figure out

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:06.680
how many yard spaces do we need in our yards, because we're

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:08.559
going to have the highest volumes that target is ever

00:01:08.559 --> 00:01:11.559
pushed through our supply chain network this fall. Should we get

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:16.440
additional off site yard space at some yards? So yeah, again,

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:18.599
concentric circles, but that's a little bit of the

00:01:18.599 --> 00:01:19.800
differentiation that I see.

